{{Infobox language |name = Abane |nativename = Baniwa of Guainia |states = [[Venezuela]] |region = Colombian border |speakers = 200? |date = 1999 |ref = <ref>Aikhenvald (1999)</ref> |familycolor = American |fam1 = [[Maipurean languages|Arawakan]] |fam2 = Northern |fam3 = [[Upper Amazon Arawakan|Upper Amazonian]] |fam4 = Orinoco |fam5 = Yavitero languages |iso3 = bvv |glotto=bani1254 |glottorefname=Baniva }}
'''Abane''' (Avane), or '''Baniwa of Guainia''', is an [[Arawakan language]] of [[Venezuela]] with a few speakers in Brazil.
Aikhenvald counts ≈ 200 speakers while ''Ethnologue'' reports the language is extinct; ''Ethnologue'' counts Xie Warekena in Brazil as a dialect of [[Guarequena language|Guarequena]] rather than of Abane as in Aikhenvald, but this only amounts to ten speakers.
==Name== Abane is one of several languages in the region called ''Baniwa''. ''Ethnologue'' (2015) distinguishes "Baniva" for the Baniwa of Guainia and "Baniwa" for the [[Baniwa of Içana]], but they are merely spelling variants, and either spelling may be used for either language.
