'''BookEnds''' is a [[non-profit organization]] based in Southern [[California]] that helps children collect books and donate them to other children in areas of low literacy. It was founded in 1998 by the mother-and-son team of Robin and Brandon Keefe in [[Agoura Hills]].<ref name="People">{{cite web | url=http://www.people.com/people/archive/article/0,,20126127,00.html | title=Novel Child | publisher=People Magazine | date=August 31, 1998 | accessdate=February 15, 2012}}</ref> Brandon, then eight years old and in the third grade, led his school class in a book drive to build a library at a local home for abused children.

BookEnds became a non-profit organization in 2002, and Robin Keefe serves as its president. It "recycles children's books" through student-led book drives and donates them to schools and youth organizations that need them. In addition to its regular book drives, it holds an annual [[Scrabble]] challenge. The organization claims to have donated more than 2 million books to 500,000 children.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bookends.org/Home%20Page|title=Bookends: Creating readers and leaders|work=BookEnds home page|accessdate=27 April 2014|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140427100942/http://www.bookends.org/Home%20Page|archivedate=27 April 2014|df=}}</ref>

BookEnds received Freeman, Freeman & Smiley Foundation Visions in Philanthropy Award in 2000, and the President's Volunteer Service Award from President [[George W. Bush|George Bush]] in 2004. Brandon and BookEnds were featured in the 2006 book ''Passionaries''.<ref>{{cite book|last=Metzler|first=Barbara R.|title=Passionaries : turning compassion into action|url=http://www.worldcat.org/title/passionaries-turning-compassion-into-action/oclc/68693646|year=2006|publisher=Templeton Foundation Press|location=Philadelphia|isbn=978-1-599471051}}</ref>

