{{Khmer language}}
This article describes the [[grammar]] of the [[Khmer language|Khmer (Cambodian) language]], focusing on the standard dialect.

==Word formation==
Khmer is primarily an [[analytic language]], with no [[inflection]]. There is some [[Derivation (linguistics)|derivation]] by means of [[prefixes]] and [[infixes]], but it is no longer always productive,<ref name = "cc">{{cite book|title=Colloquial Cambodian: A Complete Language Course |author= David Smyth|year=1995|publisher=Routledge (UK)|isbn=0-415-10006-2}}</ref> as those elements are often crystallized in words inherited from Old Khmer. Even in Old Khmer, the same affix could have multiple functions (for example, it could serve as a nominalizer in one word and as a causativizer in another).

A common prefix is {{lang|km|ការ}} [kaː-], used to convert verbs to nouns denoting actions or activities. A common infix has the form {{IPA|[-ɑm(n)-]}} or {{IPA|[-ɑn-]}} (or with other vowels), inserted after an initial consonant, especially to convert adjectives or verbs into nouns.

[[Compound (linguistics)|Compounding]] is common; in a compound of two nouns, the [[head (grammar)|head]] generally comes first, often the reverse of the English order: "duck egg" is {{lang|km|ពងទា}} {{IPA|[pɔːŋ tiə]}}, literally "egg-duck".

==Word order==
Since Khmer is an analytic language, word order is relatively fixed, as changes in word order often affect meaning. Khmer is generally a [[subject–verb–object]] (SVO) language. [[Topicalization]] is common: the topic of the sentence is often placed at the start, with the rest of the sentence a [[topic–comment|comment]] on that topic.

Like in [[English language|English]], [[prepositions]] are used rather than postpositions (words meaning "in", "on", etc. precede the noun that they govern).<ref>Huffman, Franklin. 1967. ''An outline of Cambodian Grammar''. PhD thesis, Cornell University.</ref> The language is generally [[head-initial]] so [[modifier (grammar)|modifier]]s come after the words modified (adjectives, possessives, demonstratives, [[relative clause]]s, etc. follow nouns; adverbs mostly follow verbs; and so on).

==Nouns==
Khmer [[noun]]s have no [[grammatical gender]] or [[grammatical number|singular/plural]] inflections. There are no [[Article (grammar)|articles]], but indefiniteness is often expressed by the word for "one" following the noun. Plurality can be marked by [[postnominal]] particles, numerals, or reduplication of a following adjective, which, although it is similar to intensification, is usually differentiated by context:<ref name=msc>Franklin E. Huffman, ''Modern Spoken Cambodian'', Yale University, 1970.</ref>

{{lang|km|ឆ្កែធំ}} {{IPA|[cʰkae tʰom]}} (dog large) = large dog

{{lang|km|ឆ្កែធំៗ}} {{IPA|[cʰkae tʰom tʰom]}} (dog large large) = large dogs or a very large dog

{{lang|km|ឆ្កែបី}} {{IPA|[cʰkae ɓəj]}} (dog three) = three dogs

{{lang|km|ឆ្កែខ្លះ}} {{IPA|[cʰkae kʰlah]}} (dog some) = some dogs

[[Possessive]]s are formed by placing the noun or pronoun representing the possessor after the main noun, often with the word {{lang|km|របស់}} {{IPA|[rəbɑh]}} between them. (The word {{lang|km|របស់}} is also a noun, meaning "thing".)

==Numbers and classifiers==
In Khmer, a number that indicates quantity follows the noun.

{{lang|km|សៀវភៅបួន}} {{IPA|[siəw pʰɨw ɓuən]}} (book four) = four books

Exceptions include nouns indicating passage of time such as hours or days, units of measurements and currencies, all of which function as noun classifiers without the explicit mention of what is being classified. Reversal of the order can change the meaning:

{{lang|km|បីម៉ោង}} {{IPA|[ɓəj maoŋ]}} (three hour) = three hours

{{lang|km|ម៉ោងបី}} {{IPA|[maoŋ ɓəj]}} (hour three) = three o'clock

[[Classifier (linguistics)|Classifying particles]] for use with numerals and nouns exist but are optional, unlike [[Thai language|Thai]], except in introductory clauses. They are used for clarity or formality, and number precedes classifiers.

{{lang|km|សត្វក្របីពីរ}} {{IPA|[sat krɑbəj piː]}} (animal buffalo two) = two buffaloes

{{lang|km|សត្វក្របីពីរក្បាល}} {{IPA|[sat krɑbəj piː kbaːl]}} (animal buffalo two + animal classifier) = two (head of) buffaloes

The following example illustrates the superfluous mention of what is being classified:

{{lang|km|បីរៀល}} {{IPA|[ɓəj riəl]}} (three riel) = three riels

{{lang|km|'''លុយ'''បីរៀល}} {{IPA|['''luj''' ɓəj riəl]}} ('''money''' three riel) = three riels of money or simply three riels

Counting in Khmer is based on a [[biquinary]] system (6 to 9 have the form "five one", "five two", etc.) However, the words for multiples of ten from 30 to 90 are not related to the basic Khmer numbers but are probably borrowed from Thai. The [[Khmer script]] has its own versions of the [[Arabic numerals]].

