==Adjectives==
[[Adjectives]] in Khmer follows the noun; doubling the adjective can indicate plurality or intensify the meaning (see [[#Nouns|Nouns]] above). Adjectives follow verbs when they function as adverbs. Adjectives are actually [[stative verb]]s and are used without a [[copula (linguistics)|copula]] and can be negated, like other verbs.

[[Comparative]]s are expressed using the word {{lang|km|ជាង}} /ciəŋ/: "A X /ciəŋ/ [B]" (A is more X [than B]). The most common way to express [[superlative]]s is with {{lang|km|ជាងគេ}} /ciəŋ keː/: "A X /ciəŋ keː/" (A is X-est of all).<ref name=msc/>

==Reduplication==
In Khmer, nouns and adjectives can be [[reduplication|reduplicated]].  Reduplication can occur as perfect reduplicates or by altering the rhyme of words. Khmer also uses compound reduplication in which two phonologically unrelated words with similar or identical meanings are compounded.

The [[Khmer script]] includes the symbol ៗ, which indicates that the preceding word or phrase is to be repeated.

==Verbs==
As is typical of most East Asian languages,<ref>[http://fds.oup.com/www.oup.co.uk/pdf/0-19-927311-1.pdf East and Southeast Asian Languages: A First Look] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121120111832/http://fds.oup.com/www.oup.co.uk/pdf/0-19-927311-1.pdf |date=2012-11-20 }} at Oxford University Press Online</ref> Khmer verbs do not inflect at all; [[grammatical tense|tense]] and [[grammatical aspect|aspect]] can be expressed using particles (such as កំពុង {{IPA|[kəmpuŋ]}}, placed before a verb to express [[continuous aspect]]) and adverbs (such as "yesterday", "earlier", "tomorrow"), or may be understood from context. [[Serial verb construction]] is quite common.

===Questions===
[[Yes-no question]]s can be formed by placing the particle {{lang|km|ទេ}} /teː/ at the end of a sentence. This particle can also serve as an emphatic particle (it is also used in negative sentences, as shown below), and so [[Khmer language#Intonation|intonation]] may be required to indicate that a question is being asked.

In [[wh-question|''wh''-questions]], the question word generally remains in its usual grammatical position in the sentence, rather than being brought to the start as in English (that is, [[wh-fronting|''wh''-fronting]] does not normally take place).

===Negation===
Verbs can be negated in three primary fashions, all of which convey a slightly different connotation or formality. The most common method of negation is a discontinuous construction placing {{lang|km|មិន}} "{{IPA|[mɨn]}}" (not, not to be) before the verb and ending the verb phrase with {{lang|km|ទេ}} "{{IPA|[teː]}}", which, as a stand-alone word can be either "no" or a particle contradicting a previous statement. Colloquially, the final "{{lang|km|ទេ}}" may be omitted.

{{lang|km|ខ្ញុំជឿ}} {{IPA|[kʰɲom cɨə]}} - I believe

{{lang|km|ខ្ញុំមិនជឿទេ}} {{IPA|[kʰɲom mɨn cɨə teː]}} - I don't believe

Another fairly common way of indicating negation uses {{lang|km|អត់}} (also spelled {{angbr|{{lang|km|ឥត}}}}) "{{IPA|[ɑt]}}" instead of {{lang|km|មិន}}. "{{lang|km|អត់}}", as an independent word, means "without" or "lacking" and expresses a similar connotation when used to negate a verb.

{{lang|km|ខ្ញុំអត់ឃ្លានទេ}} {{IPA|[kʰɲom ɑt khliə̯n teː]}} - "I am not hungry" or literally, "I (am) without hunger".

A third method is basically identical to the first method except {{lang|km|ពុំ}} "{{IPA|[pum]}}" is used instead of "{{IPA|[mɨn]}}".  This is used only in literary or very formal contexts.

